In its bid to institutionalize performance based culture that enables recognition and reward of high productivity at all levels within the Federal Public Service, the Office of Head of the Civil Service of the Federation in conjunction with Chartered Institute of Personnel Management (CIPM) is conducting a 3-day workshop on Objectives Setting for members of the Project Management Team on Performance Management System (PMS-PMT) and other officers in the Office of the Head of Service. The head of service, Dr. Folasade Yemi-Esan while addressing participants at the workshop which started yesterday in Abuja, revealed that the training which she said is first in the series will provide public servants with the requisite knowledge and skill to set job objectives for themselves, their colleagues and other staff in the Federal Public Service Yemi- Esan who stated that Performance Management System (PMS) is one of the eight (8) priority areas of the Federal Civil Service Strategy and Implementation Plan (FCSSIP) designed to re-engineer and re-invigorate the Federal Public Service for improved productivity as well as effective and efficient service delivery, also reiterated that efforts are being made by her office to develop a new Performance Management System due to the inherent weakness of the current Annual Performance Evaluation Report (APER). She said the new PMS is based on the principles of Accountability, Transparency, Equity and Ownership: “When the new PMS is fully operational, every individual, unit, department and institution in the public service shall be held accountable on a continuous basis to ensure that national development goals are met”. “The aforementioned further underscores the main objective of this workshop, that is to acquaint participants with the requisite knowledge and skills in setting job objectives which is a vital part of the Performance Management System (PMS) that will eventually replace the unverifiable and moribund Annual Performance Evaluation Report (APER) forms currently used to assess the performance of officers in the Public Service. Although the APER system was designed to foster and reward high performance at the institutional and individual level, there are no clearly defined national performance measures for public understanding of service delivery outcomes, she said”. Also in his response, President CIPM, Mr Wale Adediran,  charged the participant to take the workshop serious, saying that the success of the workshop was critical, not only for the office of the HOCSF, but to the country. Adediran gave assurance that the cultural transformation desired and the dream in the Federal Civil Service of the nation would be achieved in the course of the workshop. This is the life skill, it goes beyond our service to the nation, this will transform not only our country but will transform our families, it`s about getting the best productivity out of every situation, he stated.